library(xlsx)
manufacturing <- read.xlsx("~/project1/Manufacturing_Stats_by_State.xlsx", 
    sheetIndex = 1)

homeless_big <- lapply(1:10, function(i) {
    read.xlsx("~/project1/Homelessness.xlsx", sheetIndex = i)
})

I will be looking at data on the homeless population and manufacturing employment. They share a “Year” variable as well as a state variable (sort of: the data will be wrangled so that they have a matching variable). I Think comparing these datasets is interesting because it could highlight the correlation between the presence of manufacturing jobs and homelessness.

Tidying: Reshaping

## I will be looking at the data across states and years
## (2014-2015), so will need to 1.) Combine the first two
## datasets in homeless.xlsx, which contain the data for years
## 2014 and 2015.
homeless_2015 <- homeless_big[1] %>% as.data.frame
homeless_2014 <- homeless_big[2] %>% as.data.frame
homeless <- homeless_2015 %>% inner_join(homeless_2014, by = "CoC.Number")
homeless <- homeless %>% select(-"CoC.Name.y")
# 2.) Pivot longer the homeless data so that the years and
# Population type are in their own column. Also, get rid of
# the rows where the 'Year' value isn't a year.
homeless <- homeless %>% pivot_longer(cols = 3:65, names_to = "Population_Type", 
    values_to = "Population")
homeless <- homeless %>% separate(col = "Population_Type", sep = "\\.\\.", 
    into = c("Population_Type", "Year"))
homeless <- homeless %>% filter(Year %in% c(2014, 2015))

# 3.) I ultimately want to merge my datasets by state and
# year, so I want to combine all observations that take place
# in the same state. County and subdistricts are irrelevant
# to me. I will also

homeless_tidy <- homeless %>% separate(col = "CoC.Number", sep = "-", 
    into = c("State_Abbrev.", NA)) %>% mutate_at("Year", as.numeric) %>% 
    group_by(State_Abbrev., Population_Type, Year) %>% summarize(Homeless_Population = sum(Population))

# 4.) I now want to change the state names in my
# manufacturing dataframe into their respective abbreviations
# so that I'll be able to merge my homeless_tidy and the
# resulting manufacturing_tidy dataframes.
manufacturing <- manufacturing %>% rename(State_Abbrev. = Geographic.area.name)
manufacturing <- manufacturing %>% mutate(State_Abbrev. = state.abb[match(State_Abbrev., 
    state.name)]) %>% na.omit

# 5.) I want to remove the statistics data from manufacturing
# and filter out observations with confusing values (e.g.
# there is a letter where I'd expect a number).
manufacturing <- manufacturing %>% select(c(1:5, (seq(7, 21, 
    2)))) %>% mutate_at(5:13, as.numeric) %>% na.omit


# 6.) Now, since the individual type of manufacturing is not
# important to me, I want to combine the observations by
# state and year for number of workers.
manufacturing_tidy <- manufacturing %>% group_by(State_Abbrev., 
    Year) %>% summarize(Num_Workers = sum(Number.of.employees))

I have essentially cut down the manufacturing and homelessness data to a state in which they can be easily joined by their “State Abbrev.” and “Year” values.

The tidy manufacturing dataset contains 100 observations with three variables. The homeless dataset contains 2856 observations with four variables. I have inner joined the datasets by their year and state. The resulting dataset contains 2650 observations, each with 4 variables. Though each individual data set had the same values for the “Year” variable, the “State_Abbrev.” variable in the homeless dataset had five more possible values: The District of Columbia, the Virgin Islands, Puerto Rico, Guam, and NA. The remaining common values are the 50 states of the United States.

    x/lag(x)

I have found that Indiana has the highest proportion of factory workers to homeless. California has the highest chronically homeless population at 32174, while Delaware has the lowest, at only 80. Georgia had the highest net movement towards factory workers, with 2731 less homeless and 18266 more factory workers between 2014 and 2015. I found that the total mean homeless population in America is 11134 homeless, and that the median number of factory workers is 299196. Interestingly, Montana has the highest number of unsheltered homeless parenting youth under 18, at 2. The most interesting finding here is that it seems, in general, the amount of homelessness dropped from 2014 to 2015, whereas the number of factory workers rose. There must also be some sort of sampling error for unsheltered homeless, as their numbers are near 0 for numerous states.

Visualizing

combined_data2 %>% filter(Population_Type == "Total.Homeless", 
    Year == 2014) %>% ggplot(aes(x = State_Abbrev., y = Population)) + 
    geom_bar(stat = "identity", aes(fill = State_Abbrev.)) + 
    scale_y_log10() + labs(title = "Total Homeless Population by State in 2014", 
    x = "State", y = "Population") + theme_minimal() + theme(legend.position = "None", 
    axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1, size = 10)) + 
    geom_hline(yintercept = max((combined_data2 %>% filter(Population_Type == 
        "Total.Homeless", Year == 2014))$Population)) + geom_hline(yintercept = min((combined_data2 %>% 
    filter(Population_Type == "Total.Homeless", Year == 2014))$Population)) + 
    annotate("text", 45, 150000, label = "Max: 113952 in CA") + 
    annotate("text", 45, 500, label = "Min: 757 in WY")

The plot above visualizes the differences in the total homeless population per state in 2014.

maximum = max((combined_data2 %>% filter(Population_Type == "Workers", 
    Year == 2015))$Population)
minimum = min((combined_data2 %>% filter(Population_Type == "Workers", 
    Year == 2015))$Population)

combined_data2 %>% filter(Population_Type == "Workers", Year == 
    2015) %>% ggplot(aes(x = State_Abbrev., y = Population)) + 
    geom_bar(stat = "identity", aes(fill = State_Abbrev.)) + 
    labs(title = "Total Factory Worker Population by State in 2015", 
        x = "State", y = "Population") + scale_y_log10() + theme_dark() + 
    theme(legend.position = "None", axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, 
        hjust = 1, size = 10)) + geom_hline(yintercept = maximum) + 
    geom_hline(yintercept = minimum) + annotate("text", 45, 5e+06, 
    label = paste("Max:", as.character(maximum), "in CA")) + 
    annotate("text", 45, 500, label = paste("Min:", as.character(minimum), 
        "in AK"))

This plot visualizes the number of workers in manufacturing per state in 2015.

## I will compare the sheltered_homeless observations (x-axis)
## against the number of workers in that respective state
## (y-axis). Color will discern the year.
combined_data2 %>% filter(Population_Type == "Sheltered.Homeless" | 
    Population_Type == "Workers") %>% pivot_wider(names_from = ("Population_Type"), 
    values_from = ("Population")) %>% ggplot(aes(x = Sheltered.Homeless, 
    y = Workers)) + theme_light() + scale_x_log10(name = "Factory Worker Population") + 
    scale_y_log10(name = "Sheltered Homeless Population") + annotation_logticks() + 
    geom_point(aes(color = Year)) + geom_smooth(method = "lm", 
    se = F) + labs(title = "Factory Workers Against Sheltered Homeless Population by State", 
    x = "Sheltered Homeless Population", y = "Factory Worker Population")

This is a plot comparing the factory worker population in each state to that state’s sheltered homeless population. It appears that the two variables have a slight negative correlation.

Concluding Remarks

There are so many interesting variables that I could add to this tidy dataset. I believe a variable describing the longitude and latitude of the capital city of each observation could allow me to further analyze geographical causes of data peculiarities. More variables I could add are: average temperature, per capita GDP, and state income tax rate.
